data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False". Use MSTest's specialized collection assertions instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "Expected count: 3, Actual: 2" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(collection)` | When expecting exactly one item |

For the "all users are active" check, `Assert.IsTrue` with a LINQ predicate is still reasonable since there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API. You could also loop with individual asserts for clearer per-element diagnostics:

```csharp
foreach (var user in users)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User '{user.Name}' was not active");
}
```

The general rule: **use the most specific assertion available** — it produces better failure messages with zero extra effort.
